## Context
Reviewer 2 flagged the §2.1 passages on the Article 4.3 obligation as abstract
and under-argued. This child owns the concrete rewrite of the move from the
narrow incremental-cost obligation to a broader category of climate finance.
Tracker: 0141.

## Relevant passages
- `content/manuscript.qmd` §2.1 — Article 4.3 "transactional language" sentence;
  "rigorous incremental-cost framework"; welfare-theoretic-transfers sentence
  (p8); "the need for a broader category arose" (p8).

## Actions
1. Make the Article 4.3 "transactional language" claim concrete: what the treaty
   text actually obliged, who read it how.
2. State when and why the incremental-cost framework was abandoned vs extended,
   with the mechanism named (R2 substantive).
3. Ground "the need for a broader category arose" (p8) in evidence/examples, not
   assertion (R2p).
4. Bali Action Plan: explain what changed institutionally/politically between
   Article 4.3 and Decision 1/CP.13, and what triggered the shift (R2w).

## Test (prose ratchet)
- Negative guard only: no new define-by-negation, no em-dash ceiling breach in
  the revised §2.1 (`tests/test_manuscript_prose.py`). Positive editorial intent,
  if any standing decision emerges, goes to `docs/editorial-brief.md`.

## Exit criteria
- [ ] Each flagged §2.1 passage revised with concrete actors/dates/mechanisms
- [ ] Cover-letter traceability rows (R2p, R2w) updated with §ref + commit SHA
- [ ] Prose in the author's voice per `docs/style-anchor-v205.md`; `make check-fast` green
